paper_abstract: We identify two properties that for P-selective sets are effectively computable. Namely, we show that, for any P-selective set, finding a string that is in a given length's top Toda equivalence class ( very informally put, a string from Sigma(n) that the set's P-selector function declares to be most likely to belong to the set) is FP Sigma 2p computable, and we show that each P-selective set contains a weakly-P-Sigma 2p-rankable subset.
paper_title: The complexity of finding top-toda-equivalence-class members
